I am excited to attempt to port my Python program of humusic into C++. I have been learning C++ for a while now, and I think it will be a great opportunity to apply my knowledge and improve my skills.
The first step in the porting process will be to analyze the existing Python code and identify the key components and functionalities that need to be implemented in C++. I will also need to consider any libraries or dependencies that are currently being used in the Python version and find suitable alternatives in C++.

The strongest alternative to numpy I have found for C++ is the Armadillo library, which provides efficient linear algebra operations and an approachable yet powerful syntax I am thrilled to learn to use.

Upon researching Armadillo's library compotabilities, I found that it does not natively support FFT's for raw audio, only matrices. To combat this I am going to be using the lightweight yet powerful AudioFile libary by Adam Stark to convert the raw audio into something that is more functional with Armadillo's FFTs.

I will continue updating this document as I make progress on the porting process, and I am looking forward to sharing my experiences and insights along the way. I am confident that this project will not only enhance my C++ skills but also allow me to create a more efficient and robust version of humusic.
